{"cursor":"3722","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = name = Pieter Hendrik Grobbelaar honorific_suffix =\n| native_name = native_name_lang = image = Pieter Grobbelaar.jpg caption =\n| birth_date = death_date = birth_place = Porterville death_place = placeofburial = placeofburial_label =\n| placeofburial_coordinates =  nickname = birth_name = allegiance =\n| South Africa branch = South African Army serviceyears = 1933-1965 rank =\n| General servicenumber = unit = commands = battles = World War II battles_label\n| = awards = {{ plainlist |\nStar of South Africa Distinguished Service Order }}\n| relations = laterwork = signature = website = \n}}\n\nGeneral 'Pieter Grobbelaar' SSA DSO (16 September 1908 - 22 June\n1988 http://www.eggsa.org/library/main.php?g2_itemId=924904 ) was a\nSouth African military commander. He joined the South African Army as a part-\ntime Citizen Force soldier in 1929 and became a full-time Permanent Force member\nin 1933. During World War II he commanded 7th Reconnaisance Battalion as a\nLieutenant Colonel, and was second in command of 12th SA motorised infantry\nbrigade in Italy.\n\nAfter World War II he served as OC Free State Command, OC Northern Transvaal\nCommand and the SA Military College\n\nHe served as Army Chief of Staff from 1953 to 1958, as Inspector-General from\n1958 to 1959, as Deputy Commandant-General from 1959 to 1960, and as Commandant-\nGeneral, i.e. head of the South African Defence Force, from 1961 to 1965. h-\nttp://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=6243:fa-\nct-file-chiefs-of-the-sandfpast-and-present&catid=79:fact-files&Itemid=159\n","linknr":122,"url":"Pieter_Grobbelaar","recorded":1375085414,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Pieter_Grobbelaar&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Pieter_Grobbelaar&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//cr